PATIENT: ROMEO, FRANK C
NUMBER: 555555
DATE OF BIRTH: 02/12/1972
BILLING NUMBER: 40134637

ATTENDING PHYSICIAN: Louis C Lee, MD
ADMISSION DATE: 03/04/2016
HPI: Mr. ROMEO is a 43-year-old male who was riding his motorcycle approximately 5 miles per hour around the corner yesterday. He fell onto dirt onto his left side. He was wearing pants, a short sleeved shirt and a helmet. He did not hit his head or have any loss of consciousness. He landed directly onto his left flank and left chest wall side. At this time, his only complaint is pain around those regions. As part of his workup in the Emergency Department last night, he underwent a CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast which reveals edema throughout the left flank and proximal hip with asymmetric swelling and a gluteal muscle hematoma 10 cm in size. There is no evidence for underlying fracture or active extravasation seen on this study. There is no other intraabdominal pathology that was noted.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY: Anxiety and depression.
MEDICATIONS: 1. Alprazolam 0.5 mg p.o. b.i.d. 2. Citalopram 20 mg p.o. b.i.d. 3. Hydrochlorothiazide 25 mg p.o. daily. 4. Lisinopril 20 mg p.o. daily. 5. Venlafaxine 37.5 mg p.o. b.i.d. 6. Zolpidem 10 mg 1 tab p.o. q.h.s.
REVIEW OF SYSTEMS: At this time, he has no chest pain other than the tenderness along the sidewall. No shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, cardiac complaints or any other complaints. PHYSICAL EXAMINATION: VITAL SIGNS: Blood pressure is 113/59, temperature 37 degrees, heart rate of 105, respirations of 16, 98% on room air. GENERAL: The patient appears anxious and somber. HEENT: Extraocular movements intact. Mucous membranes moist. Trachea is midline. Anterior neck is soft. CARDIOVASCULAR: Heart is tachycardic rate, normal rhythm. ABDOMEN: Exam unremarkable. There is a significant amount of ecchymosis from the left subcostal region to over the left greater trochanter. There is tenderness to palpation consistent with this. There is no obvious large bulging that is seen consistent with any expanding hematoma. EXTREMITIES: No clubbing, cyanosis, or edema. There are some superficial abrasions to the left upper extremity.
LABORATORY RESULTS: White blood cell count 5,000, hemoglobin and hematocrit of 9.5 and 26 (this is versus 35 on admission about 12 hours earlier), platelets of 220.
ASSESSMENT AND PLAN: Mr. ROMEO is a 43-year-old male status post fall onto his side from a motorcycle with a contained left gluteal hematoma and some soft tissue swelling around this region. There is no evidence of active extravasation at this time. As the patient remains tachycardic, will keep him in the hospital and continue to observe. He states that when he gets anxious he easily becomes tachycardic. He has no chest complaints or shortness of breath, or any other pulmonary concerns. His chest x-ray on admission was negative. I do not feel that he requires a CT scan of the chest at this time. Will recheck his CBC again tomorrow morning and if this remains stable and his pain is under control, he may ultimately be discharged sometime this weekend. He has an abdominal binder covering the flanking gluteal regions. Will hold heparin for DVT prophylaxis and instead use SCDs and ambulation. I did encourage him to be up and around ambulating. Saline lock IV. Regular diet at this time. Dr. Waddle to cover this weekend.
